<H2><U>
<a name="figures">Important Caddo Mythological Figures</a>
</u></H2>

<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/caddi-ayo.htm">Caddi Ayo</font></U></B></I></a> (or Ayo-Caddi-Aymay.) 
This means "Sky Chief" or "Chief Above" in the Caddo language, and is the Caddo name for the Creator (God.) Sometimes the
Plains Indian term "Great Spirit" is also used. Caddi Ayo is a divine spirit and is not generally personified in Caddo folklore. 
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/village-boy.htm">Village Boy</a> and <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/wild-boy.htm">Wild Boy</font></U></B></I></a>.
These mythical twins whose mother was killed by a monster are common to the folklore of many Midwestern and Plains tribes. 
In Caddo mythology, the twins (called <I>Coninis√≠</I>) are associated with thunder and lightning.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/plains-coyote.htm">Coyote</font></a></U></B></I>.
Coyote is the trickster figure of the Caddo tribe. As in other Plains Indian mythology, Coyote is sometimes anthropomorphized into
human form and other times depicted in the shape of a coyote (sometimes both within a single story.) Caddo coyote stories range
from light-hearted tales of mischief and buffoonery, to more serious legends about the nature of the world, to ribald jokes.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/caddaja.htm">Caddaja</font></U></B></I></a>. A sort of man-eating ogre,
similar to the Two-Face and Sharp-Elbow monsters of the northern Plains tribes. In some legends the Caddaja is portrayed as
a horned serpent, more like the Cherokee Uktena.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/lost-elves.htm">Lost Elves</font></U></B></I></a>:
Ghostly little people of Caddo folklore, who steal away people who become lost in the woods.

<H2><U>
<a name="tribes">Caddo Indian Folklore</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.accessgenealogy.com/native/caddo/caddotraditions/
">Traditions of the Caddo</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Online collection of 78 Caddo legends and folktales.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.sacred-texts.com/nam/se/wsgr/index.htm
">When the Storm God Rides: Tejas and other Indian Legends</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Stories from the Alabama, Comanche and Caddo tribes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20130124002219/http://www.readperiodicals.com/201207/2781986831.html
">Caddo Sun Myths</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
An overview of traditional Caddo mythology.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.native-languages.org/caddostory.htm
">The Twin Brothers</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
https://accessgenealogy.com/native/tale-of-the-brothers-who-became-lightning-and-thunder.htm
">The Brothers Who Became Lightning And Thunder</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Caddo legends about the mythical twin heros, Thunder and Lightning.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021337/http://pyramidmesa.com/caddo1.htm
">Coyote and the Origin of Death</a>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
https://accessgenealogy.com/native/tale-of-coyote-and-the-origin-of-death.htm
">How Death Became Eternal</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The Caddo story of how death came to the world.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021344/http://pyramidmesa.com/caddo2.htm
">The Voice, the Flood and the Turtle</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Caddo myth about the flooding of the earth.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.ilhawaii.net/~stony/lore51.html
">The Buffalo Wife</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
https://accessgenealogy.com/native/tale-of-buffalo-woman.htm
">Buffalo Woman</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Caddo legend about a man who won a buffalo wife.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/CoyoteTheHungry-Caddo.html
">Coyote The Hungry</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Caddo tales of the trickster Coyote and his humorous attempts to catch turkeys.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/WhyCoyoteStoppedImitatingHisFriends-Caddo.html
">Why Coyote Stopped Imitating His Friends</a>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20111229223710/http://www.accessgenealogy.com/scripts/data/database.cgi?file=Data&report=SingleArticle&ArticleID=0024282
">Coyote Imitates His Hosts</a>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20111229222848/http://www.accessgenealogy.com/scripts/data/database.cgi?file=Data&report=SingleArticle&ArticleID=0024283
">When Coyote Imitated Woodpecker</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
More humorous Coyote stories, about the trickster trying to mimic other animals' powers.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://accessgenealogy.com/native/tale-of-the-lazy-boys-who-became-the-pleiades.htm
">The Lazy Boys Who Became The Pleiades</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Caddo legend about the origin of the Pleiades stars.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/SacredMedicineWater-Caddo.html
">Sacred Medicine Water</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Caddo legend about the creation of a sacred spring.
<BR>


